Α lament on the fleeting character of life. ‘Alas‚ good friend, do what we will, old age and death come on apace. No sacrifice can stay the hand of the pitiless lord of death ς rich and poor alike must come unto his realm, and all thy efforts to avoid war, the sea, or fell disease are vain. Thou must leave all behind that thou holdest now most dear- Then thy stored wine, thy heir, worthier than thou, will waste.' In the last strophe Horace in negative fashion returns to his philosophy of life, · Seize the pleasure of the passing bour, and do not waste your time in gathering wealth you do not use yourself. To-morrow we all die and another wastes our savings.' ⁷

Horace's thoughts frequently turned to death; but this and 4, 7 are his finest treatments of the theme. There is no indication of the date of composition. Metre, 68.
